INTRODUCTION:

DATA AND METHODS:

Data: download showshoe_data.csv Study citation: Kielland K., F. S. Chapin, R. W. Ruess. 2017. Snowshoe hare physical data in Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest: 1999-Present. Environmental Data Initiative. https://doi.org/10.6073/pasta/03dce4856d79b91557d8e6ce2cbcdc14

RESULTS:

# Start by reading in the data, cleaning up the column names, and looking at the data.

showshoe_lter <- 
  read_csv("showshoe_lter.csv") %>% 
  clean_names()
# Make a new dataframe which will be easier to work with. 

showshoe_summary <- showshoe_lter %>%
  
  # Take the character column for date and seperate it into month, data, and year.
  
  separate(date, into = c("month", "date", "year"), sep = "/") %>%
  
  # Make the time variable which we will work with (year) into a numeric variable.
  
  mutate(year = as.numeric(as.character(year))) %>% 
  
  # Change the values of year to display all four digits rather than just the last two.
  
  mutate(year = case_when(
    year == 98 ~ 1998,
    year == 99 ~ 1999,
    year == 00 ~ 2000,
    year == 01 ~ 2001,
    year == 02 ~ 2002,
    year == 03 ~ 2003,
    year == 04 ~ 2004,
    year == 05 ~ 2005,
    year == 06 ~ 2006,
    year == 07 ~ 2007,
    year == 08 ~ 2008,
    year == 09 ~ 2009,
    year == 10 ~ 2010,
    year == 11 ~ 2011,
    year == 12 ~ 2012)) %>%
  
  # Select only the variables which we want to compare by.
  
  select(year, sex, age, weight, ) %>%
  
  # Remove any rows with NA values in the weight columns.
  
  filter(weight != "NA")
showshoe_by_year <- showshoe_summary %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
    summarize(
    mean_weight = mean(weight),
    sd_weight = sd(weight),
    count = n())
showshoe_age_summary <- showshoe_summary %>% 
  filter(age == c("J", "A")) %>%
  mutate(sex = case_when(
    sex == "M" ~ "Male",
    sex %in% c("F","f") ~ "Female")) %>% 
  filter(sex == c("Male", "Female"))
ggplot(
  showshoe_age_summary,
  aes(x = year,
      y = weight,
      color = sex,
      shape = age),
  show.legend = TRUE) +
  geom_beeswarm(size = 3) +
  
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Snowshoe Hares (Lepus Americanus) Weight", 
       subtitle = "1999 - 2011: Weight (grams) Distribution by Sex and Age", 
       x = "Year", y = "Weight (grams)") +
  
  scale_color_manual(name = "Sex",
                       labels = c("Female", "Male"),
                       values = c("tomato2", "dodgerblue1")) +
  
  scale_shape_manual(name = "Age",
                     labels = c("Adults", "Juvinile"),
                     values = c(17, 18)) +
  
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(1997: 2013),
                     labels = c(1997: 2013)) +
  
  theme(text = element_text(family = "serif"),
    plot.title = element_text(size=14, face="bold"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 9, face = "bold.italic"),
    axis.title.x = element_text(size=10, face="bold", vjust = -1),
    axis.title.y = element_text(size=10, face="bold", vjust = 2),
    strip.text.x = element_text(size = 10, face = "bold.italic"),
    legend.title = element_text(size = 10, face = "bold.italic"))

Figure 1: Snowshoe Hare (Lepus Americanus) weight (grams) distribution observed in the Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest located in the Tanana valley, Alaska. Weight distributions were compared by year (1999-2011), for the years where values of; age, sex, and weight were all observed. Age was grouped by Adults and Juviniles and symbalized using shapes, sex was symbalized using color. 

ggplot(
  showshoe_summary,
  aes(x = year,
      y = weight)) +
  geom_beeswarm(size = 0.75,
                alpha = 0.5) +
  
  geom_line(data = showshoe_by_year,
            aes(x = year,
                y = mean_weight),
            color = "red",
            size = 0.75) +
  
  geom_point(data = showshoe_by_year,
            aes(x = year,
                y = mean_weight),
            color = "red",
            size = 1) +
  
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Snowshoe Hares (Lepus Americanus) Mean Weight", 
       subtitle = "1999 - 2011: Weight Distribution (grams) and Mean Weight (grams)", 
       x = "Year", y = "Weight (grams)") +
  
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(1998: 2012),
                     labels = c(1998: 2012)) +
  
  theme(text = element_text(family = "serif"),
    plot.title = element_text(size=14, face="bold"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 9, face = "bold.italic"),
    axis.title.x = element_text(size=10, face="bold", vjust = -1),
    axis.title.y = element_text(size=10, face="bold", vjust = 2),
    strip.text.x = element_text(size = 10, face = "bold.italic"),
    legend.title = element_text(size = 10, face = "bold.italic"))

Weight distributions were compared by year (1999-2011), for the years where values of; age, sex, and weight were all observed. Age was grouped by Adults and Juviniles and symbalized using shapes, sex was symbalized using color. 

# Create a summary table which represents the mean weight(g), standard deviation, sample size, and year.

kable(showshoe_by_year, 
      
      # Change the column headers to clear descriptive names.
      
      col.names = 
        c("Year", 
          "Mean Weight (gram)", 
          "Standard Deviation", 
          "Sample Size"),
      
      # Add a caption above the table which describes components for the table.
      
      caption = "Table 1: Snowshoe Hare (Lepus Americanus) weight (grams) summary statistics. Weight distributions from observations in the Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest located in the Tanana valley, Alaska. Weight distributions summarized by year (1998-2012) from various observation sample sizes.") %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = 
                  
                  # Set the table aesthetics and add a clear title to the table.
                  
                  c("striped", "hover", "condensed")) %>% 
                add_header_above(
                  c("Snowshoe Hares (Lepus Americanus) Weight Summary" = 4), 
                  color = "black", 
                  background = "lightgray", 
                  font_size = 15)
